content.description:
Start in the alcove in the right portion of the south face of Jellystone. In the left center of the alcove is a gully that provides access to the top. This route starts up and left of the base of the gully about 30 feet.

From a ledge, grab a right-slanting crack and follow this up and right about eight feet to a stance. Step up on a flake then make the crux face moves to the top.

This is the yellow line on the accompanying photo.
content.protection: Rope needed to create an anchor using the blocks on top of the cliff.
content.location: Start in the alcove in the right portion of the south face of Jellystone. In the left center of the alcove is a gully that provides access to the top. This route starts up and left of the base of the gully about 30 feet.

content.description:
Located on the far left side of the west face, left of

Cricket

.

This short route takes the center of a smooth slab past two bolts to a small roof with another bolt and then continues above to a bolted anchor.
content.protection: 3 bolts, bolted anchor/rap (all 3/8")

content.description:
Start about 100 feet right of

Comedic Timing

in an alcove. In the center of the center face is an obvious crack/flake system.

Scramble up past a couple blocks to gain a flake system. Climb the flake system to a ledge.
content.protection:
Carry a good selection of small to medium cams for the climb.

Medium to large cams and a cordelette for the anchor.
content.location:
Start about 100 feet right of

Comedic Timing

in an alcove. In the center of the center face is an obvious crack/flake system.

content.description:
Start about 15 feet right of

Comedic Timing

below the right side of a rounded face. This is about two feet left of the next vertical crack/groove.

Climb the steep face about ten feet to reach lower angled terrain. Go up the unprotected face to a terrace.

This is the pink line on the attached photo.
content.protection: Medium cams and an anchor rope are needed to TR the route.
content.location:
Start about 15 feet right of

Comedic Timing

below the next vertical crack/groove.

climbs.name: Slapstick
climbs.fa: Bob Gaines and Patty Kline, April 2008

content.description: This is a short sport climb located about 150 ft. right of Toiling Midgets. 3 bolts on a rounded arete/buttress to a 2-bolt anchor.
content.protection: 3 bolts to 2 bolt belay/rappel anchor
content.location: West Face, right side.

content.description:
Start six feet right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone. Climb a short seam to a scoop about ten feet up. Step right (crossing

Improv

to R of

Slapstick

) and climb the buttress/face to the top.
content.protection: Medium to large cams and some anchor rope are needed to set up this climb.
content.location:
Start just right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone.

climbs.name: Seinfeld
climbs.fa: Donette & Todd Swain and Hanna Mohn

content.description:
Start one foot right of the last route (a vertical groove/

Deadpan

).

Climb the thin crack and left facing corner to the slab above. Go up the slab to the terrace.

This is the blue line on the accompanying photo.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.

content.description:
Start about 100 feet right of

Comedic Timing

in a large alcove. In this alcove is a central face with an obvious finger crack on its left margin. The crack is just right of a gully.

Climb the short crack to a ledge.
content.protection: Carry small to medium cams for the route and medium to large cams and a cordelette for the anchor.
content.location:
Start about 100 feet right of

Comedic Timing

in a large alcove. In this alcove is a central face with an obvious finger crack on its left margin. The crack is just right of a gully.

content.description:
This is a 3 bolt direct start to

Toiling Midgets

(5 bolts total to a 2-bolt anchor).

Begin just left of Cricket with well-protected face climbing and stemming. At the third bolt move left (crux) and up to the second bolt of Toiling Midgets. From here a friction move to the right (height dependent,10-) leads to a crack (1 to 2 inch CD useful here). The roof is protected by a bolt, and easier than it looks if you surmount it from the right (5.8).
content.protection: 5 bolts, 1 to 2 inch CD, 2 bolt belay/rap anchor.

climbs.name: Noah
climbs.fa: Donette & Todd Swain and Hanna Mohn

content.description:
Start eight feet right of

Gleason

at the base of an easy crack. In front of the crack is an acacia bush.

Climb the crack, which turns into a flake. Continue up to the terrace above.

This is the rightmost, cream-colored line on the accompanying photo.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location:
Start eight feet right of

Gleason

at the base of an easy crack. In front of the crack is an acacia bush.

content.description:
Start six feet right of

Jelly Fungus

below an easy looking chimney.

Climb the chimney about 30 feet, then go up and slightly left in obvious cracks to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack up to a purple Camalot.
content.location:
Start six feet right of

Jelly Fungus

below an easy looking chimney. This chimney is about 25 feet left of Comedy Club.

It is the blue line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as

Cricket

, atop a large flake that leans against the base of the cliff.

Make the first couple of moves past a low bolt as for

Cricket

, then continue right and up on obvious flakes and features to reach a thin, vertical seam. Make hard moves up the seam, then follow another crack up to the top, ending near a bush.
content.protection: Medium cams and a cordelette comprise the anchor.
content.location:
Start in the same spot as Cricket, atop a large flake that leans against the base of the cliff.

It is the yellow line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as

Toiling Midgets

, down and left of

Jelly Fish

, and at the base of a shallow, right facing corner.

Climb the first 40 feet of

Toiling Midgets

(to the second bolt), then go up and left (crux) to gain a horizontal crack. Move left and up to a ledge at the base of an obvious left facing corner (The upper section of

Jelly Fish

). Climb an awkward, varnished flake to the right of the corner to the top.
content.protection:
Carry wires and TCUs for the bottom corner and medium cams for the upper flake.

Medium cams and an anchor rope to rig a TR anchor.
content.location:
Start in the same spot as

Toiling Midgets

, down and left of

Jelly Fish

, and at the base of a shallow, right facing corner.

It is the purple line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start about 30 feet right of the

Cricket

flake and just left of an easy chimney below a groove.

Stem and face climb up the steep groove to easier climbing and a ledge. Move up and left to gain an easy, wide crack that is climbed to the top.
content.protection: Medium and large cams and an anchor rope to set up a TR. The upper, easier cracks have been led.
content.location:
Start about 30 feet right of the

Cricket

flake and just left of an easy chimney below a groove.

It is the white line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

climbs.name: Jelly Fish
climbs.fa: Todd Swain, John Lauretig, Mark Butler

content.description:
Start near the left (west) end of the southwest face of Jellystone on a ledge that is about 10 feet above the ground. On this ledge are two parallel cracks in a corner. These parallel cracks are about six feet right of

Jelly Doughnut

.

Climb either of the parallel cracks about 35 feet to a chimney where a horizontal crack is on the right wall. Traverse right in the horizontal crack to gain a ledge below a prominent left facing corner. Stem up the corner (a bit exciting on the lead, smallest of C3s for pro) to the top.
content.protection:
Carry wires, the smallest Black Diamond C3s (pink & gray) and small to medium cams.

Medium cams and a long cordelette to set up a TR.
content.location:
Start near the left (west) end of the southwest face of Jellystone on a ledge that is about 10 feet above the ground. On this ledge are two parallel cracks in a corner. These parallel cracks is about six feet right of

Jelly Doughnut

.

It is the orange line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

climbs.name: Jelly Doughnut
climbs.fa: Todd & Donette Swain and Shannon Orr

content.description:
Start near the left (west) end of the southwest face of Jellystone on a ledge that is about 10 feet above the ground. On this ledge is a thin vertical crack that is just left of two parallel cracks in a corner. This thin vertical crack is about 10 feet right of

Jelly Belly

.

Climb up along the thin vertical crack to a ledge. Climb the left facing corner and crack above to the top.
content.protection:
A couple tiny wires, and a couple finger sized cams provide some protection on the route.

Medium cams and a cordelette comprise the anchor.
content.location:
Start near the left (west) end of the southwest face of Jellystone on a ledge that is about 10 feet above the ground. On this ledge is a thin vertical crack that is just left of two parallel cracks in a corner. This thin vertical crack is about 10 feet right of

Jelly Belly

.

It is the light blue line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as

Jelly Shoes

, below a chimney.

Climb about six feet up the chimney, then climb the steep, rounded, varnished arête just right of the chimney to the top.
content.protection: Medium cams and an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location:
Start in the same spot as

Jelly Shoes

, below a chimney. This chimney is about 25 feet left of Comedy Club and 35 feet right of Cricket.

It is the lime green line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start at the very left (west) end of the southwest face of Jellystone below a varnished right facing flake system near an arête.

Layback up the right facing flake (this portion of the route has been led; V1) to easier ground and a ledge. Climb the steep face and left arête of the upper block to the top (no lead pro without bolts).

V1: Start to the left of the normal start and climb the flake around to the left to the ledge (a bit easier than the normal start).
content.protection: Medium cams and anchor rope comprise the TR anchor.
content.location:
Start at the very left (west end of the southwest face) of Jellystone below a varnished flake system near an arête.

It is the red line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start in roughly the same spot as

Jello Salad

and about six feet left of

Comedy Club

.

Climb up a right leaning crack/groove about 25 feet, then go up and left past a bush. Chimney up behind a flake on the left, then climb easier ground to the top.
content.protection:
Carry small wires and TCUs for the lower crack.

Medium cams and an anchor rope comprise the anchor.
content.location:
Start in roughly the same spot as

Jello Salad

and about six feet left of

Comedy Club

.

It is the goldenrod colored line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start near the very left (west end) of the southwest face of Jellystone below a thin vertical crack and a left facing flake. This climb is about six feet right of

Jelly Bean

.

Climb the thin vertical crack and left facing flake to a ledge. Make awkward moves up a crack onto a boulder, then step left and climb an easy but unprotected face to the top (5.5 R).
content.protection: Gear to a gold Camalot for the route and medium cams and an anchor rope to set up a TR.
content.location:
Start near the very left (west end) of the southwest face of Jellystone below a thin vertical crack and a left facing flake. This is about six feet right of

Jelly Bean

.

It is the green line drawn in on the picture.

content.description:
Start about 20 feet right of

Jelly d' A

and six feet left of

Comedy Club

below a face with three horizontal cracks.

From a scooped area, climb up and left past two horizontal cracks (fixed pins). Surmount a bulge then climb up to a third horizontal (blue Camalot). Climb a short, vertical crack to easier ground.
content.protection:
Two fixed pins, a bolt and medium cams protect the route.

Medium to large cams in a horizontal under a ceiling and an anchor rope comprise the anchor.
content.location:
Start about 20 feet right of

Jelly d' A

and six feet left of

Comedy Club

below a face with three horizontal cracks.

It is the light gray line drawn in on the accompanying picture.

content.description:
Start about 10 feet right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone. Climb a groove to a scoop about ten feet up. Climb the twin cracks above, primarily using the left crack.
content.protection:
Carry a standard rack. Rappel with one rope from the

Slapstick

anchor.
content.location:
Start about 10 feet right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone.

content.description:
Begin six feet right of

Seinfeld

at the base of a right facing flake.

Go up and left on the flake, which turns into a short finger crack. Climb up and slightly right on the easy slab above to the terrace.

This is the red line on the accompanying photo.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location:
Begin six feet right of

Seinfeld

at the base of a right facing flake.

content.description:
Start in the alcove in the right portion of the south face of Jellystone. In the left center of the alcove is a gully that provides access to the top. This route starts left of the base of the gully at a crack/flake.

Climb up a series of short cracks/flakes that are left of the obvious gully. At about mid-height, trend up and left to connect with another crack/flake that leads to the top.

This is the green line on the accompanying photo.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack up to a gold Camalot.
content.location: Start in the alcove in the right portion of the south face of Jellystone. In the left center of the alcove is a gully that provides access to the top. This route starts left of the base of the gully at a crack/flake.

content.description:
Start about 15 feet right of

Comedic Timing

and just right of

Stand Up

below a groove.

Climb the awkward groove to a slab. Go up the unprotected slab to a terrace.

This is the orange line on the attached photo.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location:
Start about 15 feet right of

Comedic Timing

below a groove.

content.description:
Fun route!

Starts off of boulder at bolt (crux)...

Worth checking out...
content.protection: Starts below a single bolt to Crack. Standard rack. Pro for anchors.
content.location: SW side of Jellystone on the left side.

content.description:
Start immediately left of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone. Climb the easy but slightly awkward crack/chimney for about 40 feet to reach the

Slapstick

anchor.
content.protection:
Carry a standard rack. Rappel with one rope from the anchor on the top of

Slapstick

.
content.location:
Start just left of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone.

climbs.name: Comedic Timing
climbs.fa: FRA: Todd & Donette Swain, Claire Stapp 01-2015

content.description:
Start about 15 feet right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone. Climb an obvious, slightly right leaning groove/crack to the top. This crack forms the right side of the buttress/face of

Slapshot II

. The most awkward portion of the route is near the bottom.
content.protection:
Carry some medium cams. Scramble down right or rappel with a single rope from the

Slapstick

anchor.
content.location:
Start about 15 feet right of

Slapstick

(a three bolt route up a small, rounded arête) on the southwest face of Jellystone.

content.description:
On the left side of the alcove that is to the right of the last easy routes, is a short, steep wall.

This route climbs the obvious crack system on the wall, ending in an off-width. This is the pink line on the accompanying photo.

This route gets afternoon shade.
content.protection:
Carry gear up to a purple Camalot.

Large cams and an anchor rope needed to set up a TR.
content.location: On the left side of the alcove that is to the right of the last routes, is a short, steep wall. This route climbs the obvious crack system on the wall, ending in an off-width.

content.description:
Start about six feet right of

Cho

on the short, steep wall that is on the left side of the alcove.

Face climb up along a thin vertical seam and some huecos to the top. This is the blue line on the accompanying photo.

This route gets afternoon shade.
content.protection:
Tiny TCUs provide some protection.

Large cams and an anchor rope if you wish to set up a TR.
content.location:
Start about six feet right of

Cho

on the short, steep wall that is on the left side of the alcove.
